of comics, revising our understanding of how numerous genres emerged and upending narratives of how male auteurs built their careers. Considering issues of race, gender, and sexuality, the authors examine crime, horror, jungle, romance, science fiction, superhero, and Western comics to unpack the cultural and industrial consequences of how women were represented across a wide range of titles by publishers like DC, Timely, Fiction House, and others. This revisionist history reclaims the forgotten work done by women in the comics industry and reinserts female creators and characters into the canon of comics history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aComic books, strips, etc.xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aComic books, strips, etc.zUnited StatesxWomen authorsxHistoryy20th century. 0aComic strip characterszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHeroines in literaturexHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen cartoonistszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in literaturexHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen superheroeszUnited StatesvComic books, strips, etc.xHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acomic books, comic book history, women in comics, feminist history, gender studies, media studies, Golden Age of Comics, Superheroes, superhero, DC comics, pioneering women, pioneering women's history, pioneering women's studies.1 aDavis, Blair, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRobbins, Trina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobbins, Trina.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32411040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477324134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477324134/original  a97